						Venus, absolut&egrave; prohibita viro senescenti.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				Venus is absolutely forbidden to the aging man.
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position place="intext" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						( Romani semper animo parati, in
						( Virtute, Industria ponebant omnia.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				Romans, always prepared in mind and virtue, employed industriousness in everything. 
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position place="intext" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						( Vnicus contemnit vulgaria: 
						et contemnitur vulgaris.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				A unique man holds common things in contempt;
				a common man is held in contempt.
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		<marginalia hand="Italian" marginalia_id="Ha2.085v_0001" marginalia_continues_to="Ha2.086r_0001" marginalia_to_transcription="Ha2.086r.xml" book_id="FolgersHa2">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position place="intext" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						Cromuellus, Henrico 8.
						et Cecilius sub 
						) Elizabeta regina, maximi:
						nec arte, nec virtute,
						nec ullo valore magni:
						sed competenti literaru[m], rerumq[ue]
						scientia; industria, 
						<!-- Continues onto facing page, in text, Ha2.086r -->
					</marginalia_text>
					<person name="Oliver Cromwell"/>
					<person name="Henry VIII"/>
					<person name="Robert Cecil"/>
					<person name="Elizabeth I of England"/>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				Great were Cromwell under Henry VIII, and Robert Cecil under Queen Elizabeth.
				There is no art, virtue, or any valor of a great man, but being competent
				in letters and the knowledge of things; through industriousness... 			
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position place="tail" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						Virtus vnita, fortior.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				A unified virtue is stronger.
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position place="tail" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						multiplicata, mirabilior. humana Dea.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				Multiplied, it is more wondrous. A human goddess.
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="EN">
				<position place="left_margin" book_orientation="90">
					<marginalia_text>
						The natures of men ar not ripe in few yeares: &amp; what wittes soone mellow, to consider,
						do, &amp; suffer; with sound discretion, &amp; fitt distinction?
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
		</marginalia>
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position place="left_margin" book_orientation="90">
					<marginalia_text>
						{ Homerus, Hesiodus, 
						Pindarus, maioribus nostris optimi Poeta[e]: quia nescieru[n]t meliores. Sic optimi Oratores, Demosthenes,						
					</marginalia_text>
					<person name="Homer"/>
					<person name="Hesiod"/>
					<person name="Pindar"/>
					<person name="Demosthenes"/>
				</position>
				<position place="tail" book_orientation="90">
					<marginalia_text>
						Isocrates,
					</marginalia_text>
					<person name="Isocrates"/>
				</position>
				<position place="intext" book_orientation="90">
					<marginalia_text>
						Cicero.
					</marginalia_text>
					<person name="Cicero"/>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				Homer, Hesiod, and Pindar were much better poets than ours because they knew of no one better. Likewise with the greatest orators
				Demosthenes, Isocrates, and Cicero.			
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position place="right_margin" book_orientation="270">
					<marginalia_text>
						In vno, voluptas, et foelicitas:  In pluribus, tristitia, et miseria.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				In unity there is pleasure and happiness: in plurality there is sadness and misery.
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position place="right_margin" book_orientation="90">
					<marginalia_text>
						Juvenes admirentur, laudent, imitentur: liceat viris, a[e]mulari, excellere, obscurare celeberrimos.
						
						<!-- CG: Missing text added. -->
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				Young men admire, praise, and imitate. Men are allowed to emulate, to surpass, and to overshadow the most celebrated men.
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
